## 1. General Coding Standards
Follow these to maintain readable, maintainable C++ code. The AI should suggest adherence during generation, prioritizing modern C++ (C++11+).

@code_style_rules [
  {
    "id": "indentation",
    "rule": "Use 4 spaces for indentation. Avoid tabs.",
    "severity": "high",
    "example": "int main() {\n    return 0;\n}"
  },
  {
    "id": "naming",
    "rule": "Variables/functions: snake_case; Classes/structs: CamelCase; Constants: kUpperCamelCase or UPPER_CASE; Macros: UPPER_CASE.",
    "severity": "high",
    "example": "int user_count = 0; class UserProfile {};"
  },
  {
    "id": "comments",
    "rule": "Use Doxygen-style comments for functions, classes, and complex logic.",
    "severity": "medium",
    "example": "/** Returns user data */\nint GetUser();"
  },
  {
    "id": "error_handling",
    "rule": "Use exceptions or std::expected/std::optional for errors. Avoid raw pointers; prefer smart pointers.",
    "severity": "high",
    "example": "#include <memory>\nstd::unique_ptr<int> ptr = std::make_unique<int>(5);"
  },
  {
    "id": "type_annotations",
    "rule": "Use const correctness, auto where appropriate, and strong typing.",
    "severity": "medium",
    "example": "const int kMaxSize = 100;"
  },
  {
    "id": "headers",
    "rule": "Use include guards or #pragma once in headers.",
    "severity": "high",
    "example": "#pragma once\n// Header content"
  }
]

- Enforce line length under 100 characters.
- Prefer RAII for resource management.
- Avoid global variables; use namespaces appropriately (e.g., avoid 'using namespace std;').
- Use modern features: lambdas, range-based for loops, constexpr.

## 2. Testing and Quality Assurance
- Write unit tests for all new functions using frameworks like Google Test or Catch2.
- Aim for 80% code coverage, focusing on edge cases like null pointers and overflows.
- Run static analyzers (e.g., clang-tidy) and linters before commits.

@testing_rules {
  "required": "Unit tests for core logic, including memory safety checks",
  "tools": ["Google Test", "Catch2", "Boost.Test"],
  "best_practices": "Test exceptions, mocks, and multi-threaded scenarios"
}

## 3. Version Control and Branching Strategy
Use GitHub for version control. Follow Git Flow-inspired model, adapted for C++ projects where build artifacts may need ignoring.

@branching_strategy {
  "main_branch": "main - Production-ready code",
  "develop_branch": "develop - Integration of features",
  "feature_branches": "feature/* - New features",
  "bugfix_branches": "bugfix/* - Fixes",
  "hotfix_branches": "hotfix/* - Urgent production fixes",
  "release_branches": "release/* - Preparation for releases"
}

- Create branches using `mcp_github_create_branch` with descriptive names.
- Commit atomically: One change per commit.
- Use semantic commit messages: e.g., "feat: add login functionality", "fix: resolve memory leak in API".
- Push changes with `mcp_github_push_files` for multiple files in a single commit.
- Ignore build files in .gitignore (e.g., *.o, build/).

